<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18471122-200">
               <interp inst="t18471122-200" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18471122"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18471122-200" type="date" value="18471122"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18471122-200-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-200-18471122 t18471122-200-offence-1 t18471122-200-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>200. <persName id="def1-200-18471122" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-200-18471122" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-200-18471122" type="age" value="38"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-200-18471122" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-200-18471122" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">DAVID ADAMS</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18471122-200-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18471122-200-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18471122-200-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp>, feloniously assaulting <persName id="t18471122-name-1130" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1130" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1130" type="surname" value="CRESSY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1130" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18471122-200-offence-1 t18471122-name-1130"></join>Maria Cressy</persName>, and cutting and wounding her on the neck and throat, with intent to murder her—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNTS,</hi> with intent to do her some grievous bodily harm.—Two other <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNTS,</hi> stating her name to be <persName id="t18471122-name-1131" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1131" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1131" type="surname" value="CHALLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1131" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18471122-200-offence-1 t18471122-name-1131"></join>Maria Challis</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. COOKE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">HUDDLESTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1132" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1132" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1132" type="surname" value="CRESSY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1132" type="given" value="MSRIA"></interp>MSRIA CRESSY.</persName>
                  </hi> I live at Chapel-end, Walthamstow—I formerly lived with Henry Challis, and had six children by him—he died last May twelve month—the prisoner lodged in my house from 16th May last—he left on Friday evening, 29th Oct., on account of a quarrel which took place that evening between us—he had proposed marriage to me several times—he come home as usual that evening, about six o'clock, very much in liquor, and began to use very ill language, saying there was neither tea nor anything ready for him—that caused the words—he stopped at home about an hour, but had no tea—I locked him out on account of his language—on Sunday night, 31st Oct., I went to bed about a quarter before twelve—had not seen the prisoner between the Friday and the Sunday—my daughter and two of the children went to bed with me—my mother slept in the same room, but not in the same bed—I was awoke between five and six by a board falling on the foot of the bed, where my little boy lay—myself and two children were at the top—the little boy cried, and my daughter rose up in bed bad spoke to him, but I did not—I felt something the matter with my throat, and I said I thought my child had scratched me—my night-gown was very wet with blood—one of my little boys brought a light, and I found myself swimming with blood—I found my throat had been cut, and the blood was streaming with wound—I saw my mother pick up a handkerchief by my bedside—I had seen a handkerchief like that round the prisoner's neck on the Friday evening—there was no mark on it that I can swear to it by, only by the colour and pattern—I have washed one like it a dozen times or more—washed for the prisoner every week—the handkerchief was not in the room when I went to bed—Mr. Brown, the surgeon, attended me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1133" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1133" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1133" type="surname" value="CHALLIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1133" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA CHALLIS.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the prosecutrix's daughter, and live with her. On</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220197"></xptr>
               <p>the Sunday night I went to bed with her in the same bed—I was awoke in the morning, between five or six, by a board falling at the foot of the bed, and my little brother crying—one of my brothers afterwards lighted a candle, and I saw my mother's throat was cut, and her night-gown all bloody—I saw the neck-handkerchief after it was picked up by my grandmother—it was the same pattern as the prisoner's handkerchief—on my solemn oath the hand<lb></lb>kerchief was not in the room when I went to bed—I saw the prisoner wear<lb></lb>ing that handkerchief on the Saturday morning, when he came to the window for his victuals—he was refused admittance, the door was locked.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I suppose you cannot speak to the identify of the handker<lb></lb>chief, farther than saying it was the same pattern? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1134" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1134" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1134" type="surname" value="CRESSY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1134" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>SOPHIA CRESSY.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the prosecutrix's mother, and live with her. The prisoner lodged at her house previous to 31st Oct.—for the last three months he has conversed with me respecting his marrying my daughter—I told him he had better not think anything of her, as she had a large family—he spoke of marrying her several times—I saw him on Friday, 29th Oct.—there was a quarrel about the tea not being ready when he came home in the evening—there were a great many words, and, being persuaded by the police, we turned him out of doors, and would not let him rest in the dwelling that night—on Saturday morning he came to the window, and asked for his victuals—I gave him the box he had his victuals in, and he took what he had, out of the box at the window—I slept in my daughter's room on the Sunday night, and was awoke by the falling of a foot-board—I afterwards, when the light was brought, saw the state in which her throat was—I picked up a handker<lb></lb>chief which laid by the bedside, and laid it on the bed—I am sure that hand<lb></lb>kerchief was not in the room on the previous night—I have seen the prisoner wearing a handkerchief of the same colour as that, and have washed it several times while he lodged in the house—there is no particular mark about it—to the best of my knowledge it is the same—he had the same sort of handker<lb></lb>chief on Saturday morning—when I found the handkerchief, I had a strong suspicion, the instant I saw it, that it was the prisoner's—I was the first that went down stairs—I went to the back door—it was open, and there was a ladder placed, so that a person could get through the window of the room where the witness Howe used to sleep—the ladder belonged to Mr. Soames, a farmer, living near—I saw a pair of boots which were found in the privy—they were the prisoner's boots—a woman of the name of Adams showed them to me—they are the same that the policeman, James M'Colloch, has the custody of—I did not fasten up the house the night before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1135" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1135" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1135" type="surname" value="HOWE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1135" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HOWE.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a labourer, and live in the prosecutrix's house. On the Sunday night I went to bed between eleven and twelve o'clock—my room window was fastened—one of the panes of glass had been broken, and a piece of paper fastened over it, to keep out the air—I awoke in the morning little before six—I saw the state the prosecutrix's throat was in—I was the first that went down stairs; and half-way down the stairs, nearly at the bottom, I found the top part of a razor-case—those were the stairs leading up to the room where the prosecutrix was—I found the other part of the razor-case in the back kitchen window—I had seen that razor-case in the house before—the prisoner used to use it—I have seen it in the house when he was there—it used to be kept on the back kitchen shelf—I went out at the back door; it was closed, but unfastened—I know it had been fastened the night before—it opened from within—I went outside, and saw a ladder placed at the right side of the window, by which a person could get into the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220198"></xptr>
               <p>room I used to occupy—I went up the ladder—the window was closed, but not fastened—it had been fastened the previous night—I had worn a pair of boots on the Sunday, and afterwards put them in the kitchen, under a chair—I missed them—the policeman, Ward, afterwards showed them to me—I found the paper removed from the window—it had been safe the night before—a person from the outside could have put his hand through the place where the paper was, and open the window.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you lodging there before the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—nobody used this razor-case but him—I took notice of this end of it, so as to be able to identify it—I cannot say it is the same razor-case that he used, only that it is like it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. COOK.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you describe to Ward the shoes you had lost before they were shown to you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1136" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1136" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1136" type="surname" value="WARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1136" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WARD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, N</hi> 144.) I produce a pair of shoes which I get from the prisoner when he was in custody at Hford gaol—he was wearing them—I had previously, on that same day, received a description of a pair of shoes from Howe, which corresponded with these shoes—they are very remarkable—there are two rows of nails outside the heel, one row inside, one row round the sole, and a few knocked out of each row, besides a patch on the right shoe, where there are two holes—Howe told me of all this before, and, finding they corresponded with his description, I took possession of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1137" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1137" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1137" type="surname" value="WHALE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1137" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY WHALE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, N</hi> 148.) On Tuesday, 2nd Nov., I saw the prisoner on the road to Chingford—I asked if he had heard about the woman that had had her throat cut at Chapel-end—he said he had—(I did not at that time know it was the prisoner)—I said, "I suppose, then, there is some truth in it—he said he did not know much about it, for he had only heard it himself—I asked where he lived—he said at Hale-end—I asked where he slept on the night of 1st Nov.—he said he had slept in the forest—I saw that he had his left hand in his pocket, and when it was taken out I saw that he had lost two fingers—upon that I said that he was the very man that was suspected to have done it—he did not say anything, but appeared very much agitated—I took him into custody—as we were going along he asked me if the woman's throat was cut very badly, and whether she was dead—I told him I did not know, I knew very little about it—he said, "Ah! I was drunk at the time"—as we were going along, my attention was called away from him, and he ran away—I overtook him—he had no neckerchief on when I took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had he when you first saw him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—he had on a pair of blucher boots like those that were afterwards in Ward's possession—I can<lb></lb>not tell whether they were the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1138" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1138" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1138" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1138" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HUNTER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman N</hi> 357.) On Monday, 1st Nov., I saw Mrs. Cressy—I afterwards searched round the premises, and in the privy of the adjoining yard found these boots, which I produce—there is a row of houses—the back premises of Mrs. Cressy are only separated from the adjoining yard by a small temporary wooden fence, which was broken down, so that anybody could get over—I saw footmarks leading from Mr. Soames' farm-yard, across a ploughed field, to the back of these yards—some of the foot-marks were perfect enough to enable me to notice the marks on them—after finding the boots I went with Serjeant M'Culloch to the field—I had not noticed the impressions at the time I found the boots, but about twenty minutes afterwards—the boots were out of my possession about five minutes—Sophia</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184711220199"></xptr>
               <p>Cressy had them to take into the house—she did not go with them to the field, to my knowledge—I saw M'Culloch put the boots into the impress<lb></lb>sions in the field—he put them down into the marks, and afterwards made an impression with them—I only saw him put them into one mark—there were impressions all across the field—he put the boots into more than one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1139" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1139" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1139" type="surname" value="M'CULLOCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1139" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES M'CULLOCH</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant N</hi> 36.) I compared these boots with the footmarks—I first made an impression alongside the other, and then com<lb></lb>pared them—they agreed—I did that in several places—I never put the boots into the mark—I could see the footsteps right across the field—they were all the same sort of footsteps—they were coming in a direction towards Mrs. Cressy's house—I showed those boots to Mrs. Cressy's mother.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1140" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1140" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1140" type="surname" value="CRESSY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1140" type="given" value="SOPHIA"></interp>SOPHIA CRESSY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> These are the prisoner's boots—I know them by the heels being broken out in several places, and by moving them about, the house from place to place when he has been gone to bed in the house—the policeman brought them to me before he took them to the field—I think I had them for an hour or two, but I cannot recollect—they were kept in the back kitchen during that time—I did not go with them to the field.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1141" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1141" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1141" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1141" type="given" value="JOHN DALLISON"></interp>JOHN DALLISON BROWN.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a surgeon, at Walthamstow. On 1st Nov. I was called to the prosecutrix—I found a wound on the left side of her throat extending about three inches—the wound generally was superficial, with the exception of one part, where I presume the instrument had pene<lb></lb>trated rather deeper through the muscles, and consequently had produced considerable hemorrhage—no doubt a sharp instrument such as a razor must have inflicted it—it was a clean cut—there was a considerable degree of ex<lb></lb>haustion from loss of blood, so much so that for several days I considered her life in danger—that was attributable to the loss of blood, and to her being in an impoverished state of constitution, being a pauper—the wound was over a vital part—it had commenced by the windpipe, and had passed over the carotid artery—if it had wounded her there, immediate death would have followed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1142" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1142" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1142" type="surname" value="M'CULLOCH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1142" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES M'CULLOCH</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I found no footmarks leading from the house—the road comes close up to the house, and there would be no marks there—there were footmarks, but not similar to the prisoner's—there were some similar to Howe's shoes, but I could not tell exactly—they were not found until the 6th, and it was too late then to make any comparison.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18471122-name-1143" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1143" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1143" type="surname" value="HOWE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18471122-name-1143" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HOWE</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The shoes produced are mine.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I know nothing of it; I am quite innocent.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18471122-200-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18471122-200-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18471122-200-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                     <hi rend="smallCaps">GUILTY</hi> 
                     <hi rend="italic">on</hi> 1<hi rend="italic">st Count.</hi>
                  </rs> Aged 38.—<hi rend="italic">
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">
                        <rs id="t18471122-200-punishment-170" type="punishmentDescription">
